Preview: Simple Returns vs. Logarithmic Returns (log returns)

very often log returns are used instread of simple returns.

  • Favourable characteristics of log returns
  • Drawbacks of simple returns

    • problem: Many Students/Practitioners feel uncomfortabe with log returns.

    Discreate Compounding

    Annual compounding -> interest accrue once a year at the end of the year
    Quarterly Compounding -> interest accrue once a quarter at the end of the quarter
    Monthly Compounding -> interest accrue once a month at the end of the month

    Ex: 100 initial investmen and use 2% montly compounding. Therefore, for a year 100 * 1.02^12 which around $127

    In[91]:
    100 * (1.02**12) #calculation
    Out[91]:
    126.82417945625456

    Continous Compounding

    -> interest are calculated and added to your saving account continously (infinitely large number of compounding events). -> contionus exponential growth that can be observed in nature

    Prices of traded financial instruments change (approx.) continuously.
    -> intuitively, it makes a lot of sense to work with log returns.

    Simple Returns vs Log Returns

    Log returns are additive over time. Simple returns are not additive over time (but they can be multiplied/compounded)
    Simple returns easily mislead us about the number it makes

    Kesimpulan

    Log returns lebih stabil, dapat dijumlahkan, dan akurat untuk analisis keuangan.

Cocok untuk penghitungan multi-periode, CAGR, dan normalisasi harga.

Simple returns bisa menyesatkan, terutama saat digunakan untuk rata-rata atau akumulasi jangka panjang.

    Gunakan log returns untuk analisis profesional dan robust, terutama dalam riset keuangan, kuantitatif trading, dan manajemen risiko.

    Mean-Variance Analysis has one major shortcoming: it assumes that financial returns follow a normal distribution. That's (typically) not true.
    -> standard deviation of returns underestimates the true/full risk of an investment as it fails to measure 'Tail Risks'.

    do USDJPY Returns follow a Normal Distribution?
    A normal distributed random variable can be fully described by its

  • Mean
  • Standard Deviation

    • Higher central moments are zero:
  • Skew = 0 (measures symmetrie around the mean)
  • (Excess) Kurtosis = 0 (positive excess kurtosis -> more observations in the 'tails')
    • In[132]:

    -> Assuming that USDJPY Returns (generally) follow a Normal Distribution, there is 0% probability that we get that extreme outcomes in a sample.

    USDJPY Returns don't follow a Normal Distribution as they exhibit 'Fat Tails'. Extreme Events/Outcomes are not reflected in the Mean-Variance Analysis. The Standard Deviation of Returns underestimates true Risk.

    Dengan demikian, USDJPY tidak dalam Normal Distribution karena dia exhibit extreme values of returns dan bila dia mengikuti distribusi normal adalah 0% dia akan menghasilkan hasil ekstrim. Ini pun telah divalidasi dari gambar dan test statistics.

    Be careful, youll always find (sub-)periods with low returns & high risk and high returns & low risk.

    • Analysis Period must be sufficiently long to reduce impact of random noise.
    • Analysis Period should be as short as possible and should only include the latest trends / regimes.
    • Commonly used reporting period: 3 Years / 36 Months

    Interpretation

    You can observe how the expected return and risk (volatility) of the USD/JPY forex pair change over time.

Useful for risk management, regime detection, or volatility forecasting.

    Main Concept: Rolling Statistics

    Rolling statistics (like rolling mean and rolling standard deviation) are used to:

    Analyze how returns and risk evolve over time

Identify changing regimes in performance

Avoid relying too heavily on long-term averages that may hide important fluctuations

    Why Use Rolling Statistics?
    Problem with Using Full-Period Averages:

    The 7-year mean return (25.4%) and volatility (27.3%) may not reflect current market conditions

Markets, technologies, and competitive environments change rapidly (especially in IT)

    Rolling Window Solution:

    Use a moving time window, e.g. 252 trading days (~1 year)

At each point in time, compute return and risk based on the latest 252 data points

This helps reveal temporal shifts in performance and volatility

    so simply it show how return and std change over time hence past performance doesnt reflect future performance because the return is changing

    Another Example: Simple Moving Average (Prices) - SMA

    In[192]:

    In[193]:

plt.show()

    Short Selling / Short Position

    why we need to use log return:
    Simple returns depend on where you start So:

    +50% and 50% dont cancel each other

+13.64% and 13.64% are not opposites

    therefore, they are not symmetric.

    -> For simple returns: long position returns != short position returns * (-1)
    -> For log returns: long position returns == short position returns * (-1)

    Covariance and Correlation

    Do instruments/assets move together (and to what extent)?

    Three cases:

    • unrelated (no relationship/correlation)
    • moving together (positive relationship/correlation)
    • moving in opposite directions (negative relationship/correlation)

    -> Correlation between instruments/assets play an important role in portfolio management.

    0.0762746992301423

    While log returns are time-additive, they are not asset-additive.__
    (While simple returns are not time-additive, they are asset-additive.)

    Practical Implication:

    If you're building or analyzing a portfolio made up of multiple assets at a single point in time, use simple returns.

If you're analyzing one asset over time, then log returns are better due to time-additivity (e.g., for compounding, continuous models)

    Margin Trading & Levered Returns

    Definition: "Margin trading refers to the practice of using borrowed funds from a broker to trade a financial asset, which forms the collateral for the loan from the broker." (Investopedia.com)

    In Simple Words: Investors dont pay the full price but they get the full benefit (less borrowing costs).

    Its a two edged sword: Leverage amplifies both gains and losses.
    In the event of a loss, the collateral gets reduced and the Investor either posts additional margin or the brokers closes the position.

    Hypothesis: For (highly) profitable Investment: The more leverage, the better?

    What happens when leverage greater than...?

    In[251]:
    -1 / usdjpy.Simple_Ret.min()
    Out[251]:
    26.845988697186296
    1. With Leverage you can (theoretically) lose more than the initial Margin (in practice: margin call / margin closeout before)
    2. Even for (highly) profitable instruments: "The more leverage the better" does not hold.
    3. Its a two edged (non-symmetrical) sword: Leverage amplifies losses more than it amplifies gains.
